('unilag','Use of English','Oral English and Phonology',NULL,'What is the difference between a phoneme and an allophone?','A phoneme is a speech sound, while an allophone is a variant of that sound','A phoneme is a variant of a speech sound, while an allophone is the speech sound itself','A phoneme is a written symbol, while an allophone is a spoken sound','A phoneme is a spoken sound, while an allophone is a written symbol','A','A phoneme is a distinct unit of sound in a language, while an allophone is a variant of that sound that occurs in specific contexts.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Oral English and Phonology',NULL,'Which of the following is an example of a assimilation process in speech?','The pronunciation of ''hand'' as /hænd/','The pronunciation of ''black bird'' as /blæk bɜrd/','The pronunciation of ''hand'' as /hɑnd/','The pronunciation of ''black bird'' as /blæg bɜrd/','D','Assimilation is a process where one sound is influenced by a nearby sound, resulting in a change in pronunciation. In this example, the /k/ sound in ''black'' is replaced by a /g/ sound due to the influence of the following /b/ sound.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Oral English and Phonology',NULL,'What is the term for the process of pronouncing a word with a different vowel sound than its standard pronunciation?','Metathesis','Assimilation','Dissimilation','Vowel shift','D','Vowel shift refers to a change in the pronunciation of a word''s vowel sound, often resulting in a different pronunciation than the standard or expected one.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Oral English and Phonology',NULL,'Which of the following statements about intonation is true?','Intonation is used to distinguish between questions and statements','Intonation is used to indicate the mood of the speaker','Intonation is used to convey meaning and attitude','All of the above','D','Intonation is a crucial aspect of spoken English, and it serves multiple functions, including distinguishing between questions and statements, indicating the mood of the speaker, and conveying meaning and attitude.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
