('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Which of the following words is a pronoun?','Happy','Run','He','Big','C','A pronoun is a word that takes the place of a noun, and ''he'' is an example of a pronoun.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'What part of speech is the word ''quickly'' in the sentence ''She quickly finished her homework.'',','Adverb','Adjective','Noun','Verb','A','The word ''quickly'' is an adverb because it modifies the verb ''finished''.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Identify the part of speech of the word ''big'' in the sentence ''The big house is mine.'',','Adverb','Verb','Adjective','Noun','C','The word ''big'' is an adjective because it modifies the noun ''house''.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Which of the following words is a preposition?','Happy','Run','In','Big','C','A preposition is a word that shows the relationship between a noun or pronoun and other words in a sentence, and ''in'' is an example of a preposition.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'What part of speech is the word ''and'' in the sentence ''I like reading books, and I like writing stories.'',','Conjunction','Interjection','Noun','Verb','A','The word ''and'' is a conjunction because it connects two clauses in the sentence.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Identify the part of speech of the word ''yell'' in the sentence ''The crowd will yell when the concert starts.'',','Noun','Verb','Adverb','Adjective','B','The word ''yell'' is a verb because it shows action in the sentence.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Which of the following words is an interjection?','Happy','Oh','He','Big','B','An interjection is a word that expresses emotion or feeling, and ''oh'' is an example of an interjection.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'What part of speech is the word ''well'' in the sentence ''She sings well.'',','Adverb','Adjective','Noun','Verb','A','The word ''well'' is an adverb because it modifies the verb ''sings''.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Identify the part of speech of the word ''city'' in the sentence ''The city is very big.'',','Adjective','Verb','Noun','Adverb','C','The word ''city'' is a noun because it refers to a person, place, or thing.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Which of the following words is a auxiliary verb?','Go','Will','Happy','Big','B','An auxiliary verb is a verb that helps to form the tense, mood, or voice of another verb, and ''will'' is an example of an auxiliary verb.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'What part of speech is the word ''between'' in the sentence ''The difference between the two options is significant.'',','Preposition','Conjunction','Interjection','Adverb','A','The word ''between'' is a preposition because it shows the relationship between the noun ''difference'' and the nouns ''options''.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Identify the part of speech of the word ''that'' in the sentence ''The book that I read was interesting.'',','Pronoun','Adverb','Adjective','Subordinating conjunction','D','The word ''that'' is a subordinating conjunction because it introduces a subordinate clause in the sentence.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'Which of the following words is an article?','Happy','The','He','Big','B','An article is a type of adjective that modifies a noun, and ''the'' is an example of a definite article.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Parts of Speech',NULL,'What part of speech is the word ''however'' in the sentence ''I wanted to go to the party; however, I was tired.'',','Conjunction','Interjection','Adverb','Preposition','A','The word ''however'' is a conjunction because it connects two clauses in the sentence, although it can also be considered an adverb in some contexts.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'The manager, along with his employees, _______ hard to meet the deadline.','works','work','is working','are working','B','The subject-verb agreement rule states that a singular subject takes a singular verb, while a plural subject takes a plural verb. However, when using ''along with'', the subject is considered singular if it is a single entity, but in this case ''his employees'' makes the subject plural, hence ''work'' is the correct answer.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'If I _______ you, I would not have come to the party.','was','wasn''t','am','were','B','The correct answer is ''wasn''t'' because it is in the second conditional tense, which is used to express hypothetical or uncertain situations in the past. The sentence should read ''If I weren''t you'' but ''wasn''t'' is used in informal language.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'By the time I _______ my homework, it was already midnight.','finish','finished','was finishing','had finished','B','The correct answer is ''finished'' because it is in the simple past tense, which is used to describe completed actions in the past. The sentence describes two completed actions: finishing homework and the time being midnight.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'If it _______ rain, we would have gone to the beach.','didn''t','doesn''t','hadn''t','won''t','A','The correct answer is ''didn''t'' because it is in the third conditional tense, which is used to express hypothetical or uncertain situations in the past with a past condition. The sentence describes a past situation where it rained and a possible past action that could have happened if it hadn''t rained.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'I wish it _______ snow in Lagos.','snows','snowed','were snowing','would snow','B','The correct answer is ''snowed'' because it is in the subjunctive mood, which is used to express wishes or hypothetical situations. The sentence describes a situation where the speaker wishes it snowed in Lagos, but it''s not possible.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'By next year, I _______ English for five years.','will have studied','would have studied','am studying','study','A','The correct answer is ''will have studied'' because it is in the future perfect tense, which is used to describe an action that will be completed at a specific point in the future. The sentence describes the duration of studying English up to a point next year.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'The teacher said, ''_______ your books''.','Take','Taking','To take','Take out','A','The correct answer is ''Take'' because when reporting orders or instructions, the verb remains in the imperative mood, which is the base form of the verb. The sentence describes a direct order from the teacher.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'I _______ to the gym three times a week.','goes','go','am going','have gone','B','The correct answer is ''go'' because it is in the simple present tense, which is used to describe habitual or routine actions. The sentence describes a regular action of going to the gym.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'The company _______ a new policy last year.','implements','implemented','is implementing','will implement','B','The correct answer is ''implemented'' because it is in the simple past tense, which is used to describe completed actions in the past. The sentence describes a completed action of implementing a new policy last year.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'If I had studied harder, I _______ the exam.','pass','passed','would pass','would have passed','D','The correct answer is ''would have passed'' because it is in the third conditional tense, which is used to express hypothetical or uncertain situations in the past with a past condition. The sentence describes a past situation where the speaker did not study hard and a possible past action that could have happened if they had studied harder.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'By the time they _______ their project, they had already spent a year on it.','finish','finished','were finishing','had finished','B','The correct answer is ''finished'' because it is in the simple past tense, which is used to describe completed actions in the past. The sentence describes two completed actions: finishing the project and spending a year on it.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'I _______ my car for ten years now.','own','owns','have owned','am owning','C','The correct answer is ''have owned'' because it is in the present perfect tense, which is used to describe an action that started in the past and continues up to the present. The sentence describes the duration of owning a car from the past up to the present.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'The new employee _______ the task immediately.','starts','started','is starting','will start','B','The correct answer is ''started'' because it is in the simple past tense, which is used to describe completed actions in the past. The sentence describes a completed action of starting a task immediately.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'If it _______ rain, the crops would have grown.','didn''t','doesn''t','hadn''t','won''t','A','The correct answer is ''didn''t'' because it is in the third conditional tense, which is used to express hypothetical or uncertain situations in the past with a past condition. The sentence describes a past situation where it rained and a possible past action that could have happened if it hadn''t rained.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Tense and Concord',NULL,'I wish I _______ more time to finish the project.','have','has','had','would have','C','The correct answer is ''had'' because it is in the subjunctive mood, which is used to express wishes or hypothetical situations. The sentence describes a situation where the speaker wishes they had more time to finish the project, but it''s not possible now.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the idiom ''break a leg'' mean?','To wish someone bad luck','To wish someone good luck','To tell someone to be careful','To advise someone to give up','B','The idiom ''break a leg'' is used to wish someone success before a performance or a challenging situation.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The proverb ''a bird in the hand is worth two in the bush'' means that','it''s better to take risks and try to get more','it''s better to appreciate what you already have','you should always try to get the best','you should never be satisfied with what you have','B','This proverb advises people to appreciate what they already have rather than taking a risk to get more.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the idiom ''beat around the bush'' mean?','To talk directly and clearly','To avoid talking about something directly','To give a straightforward answer','To refuse to answer a question','B','The idiom ''beat around the bush'' means to avoid talking about something directly or clearly.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The idiom ''cost an arm and a leg'' means that something is','very cheap','reasonably priced','extremely expensive','free','C','The idiom ''cost an arm and a leg'' is used to describe something that is very expensive.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the proverb ''actions speak louder than words'' mean?','That words are more important than actions','That actions are more important than words','That words and actions are equally important','That it''s better to do nothing','B','This proverb means that it''s not what you say that matters, but what you actually do.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The idiom ''cut to the chase'' means','to start talking about something else','to get to the point or the most interesting part of a conversation','to change the subject','to stop talking altogether','B','The idiom ''cut to the chase'' is used to ask someone to get to the point or the most interesting part of a conversation.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the idiom ''give someone the cold shoulder'' mean?','To show someone affection','To ignore or show indifference to someone','To talk to someone politely','To argue with someone','B','The idiom ''give someone the cold shoulder'' means to deliberately ignore or show indifference to someone.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The proverb ''all''s fair in love and war'' means that','people should always follow the rules','anything is acceptable in extreme circumstances','love and war are unrelated','only love is important','B','This proverb suggests that in extreme circumstances, such as in love or war, people may do things they wouldn''t normally do.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The idiom ''bend over backwards'' means to','refuse to help someone','do the minimum required to help someone','go out of your way to help someone','expect something in return for helping someone','C','The idiom ''bend over backwards'' means to go out of your way to help someone or accommodate their needs.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the idiom ''burn the midnight oil'' mean?','To go to bed early','To work late into the night','To take a break from work','To sleep during the day','B','The idiom ''burn the midnight oil'' means to work late into the night, often to meet a deadline.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The idiom ''cry over spilt milk'' means','to worry about something that has already happened and can''t be changed','to be happy about something that has happened','to try to change the past','to ignore the present','A','The idiom ''cry over spilt milk'' means to worry or be upset about something that has already happened and can''t be changed.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The proverb ''pride goes before a fall'' means that','being proud is a good thing','being proud can lead to a downfall','being humble is a weakness','being proud is necessary for success','B','This proverb warns that being too proud or arrogant can lead to a downfall or failure.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'What does the idiom ''rain on someone''s parade'' mean?','To join in and celebrate with someone','To spoil or ruin someone''s plans or event','To ignore someone''s plans or event','To help someone with their plans or event','B','The idiom ''rain on someone''s parade'' means to spoil or ruin someone''s plans or event, often by saying or doing something negative.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The idiom ''take it with a grain of salt'' means to','believe something completely','be skeptical or cautious about something','ignore something entirely','get angry about something','B','The idiom ''take it with a grain of salt'' means to be skeptical or cautious about something, and not to take it at face value.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Idioms and Proverbs',NULL,'The proverb ''the pot calling the kettle black'' means that','someone is being honest and fair','someone is being hypocritical','someone is being generous','someone is being kind','B','This proverb describes a situation where someone accuses another person of something that they themselves are guilty of, which is considered hypocritical.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is meant by ''register'' in the context of language use?','A person''s name in a hotel guestbook','A variety of language used in a particular context','A type of font style','A linguistic term for a dialect','B','Register refers to a variety of language used in a particular context, such as formal or informal language.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which of the following best describes the term ''jargon''?','A regional dialect','A type of slang','The specialized language of a particular profession','A language variety used by a social class','C','Jargon refers to the specialized language used by a particular profession or group, often unfamiliar to outsiders.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is the difference between a dialect and a register?','A dialect is a regional variety, while a register is a social variety','A dialect is a social variety, while a register is a regional variety','A dialect is a type of language, while a register is a type of font','A dialect is a language variety, while a register is a language style','A','A dialect refers to a regional or social language variety, while a register refers to a language variety used in a particular context or for a particular purpose.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which variety of English is often used in formal situations, such as business meetings or academic writing?','Informal English','Colloquial English','Formal English','Slang','C','Formal English is often used in formal situations, such as business meetings or academic writing, to convey respect and professionalism.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is an example of a social dialect?','Cockney Rhyming Slang','American English','Australian English','All of the above','A','Cockney Rhyming Slang is an example of a social dialect, which is a language variety associated with a particular social group or class.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is meant by ''code-switching'' in language use?','Switching between two languages','Switching between two dialects','Switching between two registers','All of the above','D','Code-switching refers to the practice of switching between two or more languages, dialects, or registers in a single conversation or interaction.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which of the following best describes the term ''idiolect''?','A person''s unique variety of language','A regional dialect','A social dialect','A language variety used by a particular profession','A','An idiolect refers to a person''s unique variety of language, shaped by their individual experiences, background, and personality.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is the purpose of using formal language in academic writing?','To convey a sense of friendship','To convey a sense of authority and expertise','To convey a sense of informality','To convey a sense of humor','B','Formal language is used in academic writing to convey a sense of authority and expertise, and to present information in a clear and objective manner.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which variety of English is often used in informal situations, such as conversations with friends?','Formal English','Informal English','Colloquial English','Slang','B','Informal English is often used in informal situations, such as conversations with friends, to convey a sense of relaxation and camaraderie.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is an example of a regional dialect?','Cockney Rhyming Slang','Scouse','Geordie','All of the above','D','Cockney Rhyming Slang, Scouse, and Geordie are all examples of regional dialects, which are language varieties associated with particular geographic regions.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which of the following best describes the term ''style''?','A language variety used in a particular context','A language variety used by a particular social group','A language variety characterized by a particular tone or attitude','A language variety used by a particular profession','C','Style refers to a language variety characterized by a particular tone or attitude, such as formal, informal, serious, or humorous.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is the difference between a dialect and a language?','A dialect is a language variety, while a language is a standard variety','A dialect is a standard variety, while a language is a language variety','A dialect is a type of language, while a language is a type of dialect','A dialect is a regional variety, while a language is a national variety','A','A dialect is a language variety, while a language is a standard variety, often used as a reference point for language instruction and communication.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which variety of English is often used in technical or specialized contexts, such as engineering or medicine?','Formal English','Informal English','Technical English','Colloquial English','C','Technical English is often used in technical or specialized contexts, such as engineering or medicine, to convey complex information in a precise and accurate manner.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'What is meant by ''diglossia'' in language use?','The use of two languages in a single conversation','The use of two dialects in a single conversation','The use of two languages in a particular society or community','The use of two registers in a single conversation','C','Diglossia refers to the use of two languages in a particular society or community, often with one language used for formal or official purposes and the other language used for informal or everyday purposes.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Register and Varieties',NULL,'Which of the following best describes the term ''linguistic variation''?','The use of different languages in a particular context','The use of different dialects in a particular context','The use of different language varieties in a particular context','The use of different language styles in a particular context','C','Linguistic variation refers to the use of different language varieties, such as dialects, registers, or styles, in a particular context or for a particular purpose.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Choose the correctly constructed sentence from the options','The dog run quickly across the field','The dog runs quickly across the field','The dog running quickly across the field','The dog to run quickly across the field','B','Subject-verb agreement is essential in sentence construction. The subject ''dog'' is a singular noun, so the verb ''runs'' must also be singular to agree with it.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Identify the sentence that is in the passive voice','The manager wrote the report','The report was written by the manager','The report is being written by the manager','The manager is writing the report','B','In the passive voice, the focus is on the action rather than the doer. The sentence ''The report was written by the manager'' emphasizes the report, not the manager.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Which of the following sentences is an example of a compound sentence?','I went to the store, and I bought some milk','I went to the store because I needed milk','I went to the store, but it was closed','I went to the store; therefore, I bought some milk','A','A compound sentence contains two independent clauses joined by a conjunction. The sentence ''I went to the store, and I bought some milk'' contains two independent clauses (''I went to the store'' and ''I bought some milk'') joined by ''and''.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Choose the sentence that is in the correct order of subject, verb, and object','The book the student reads','The student the book reads','The student reads the book','Reads the student the book','C','The basic sentence structure in English is subject-verb-object (SVO). The sentence ''The student reads the book'' follows this order.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Which of the following sentences uses a relative clause correctly?','The book, which the author wrote, is on the bestseller list','The book, that the author wrote, is on the bestseller list','The book, who the author wrote, is on the bestseller list','The book, what the author wrote, is on the bestseller list','A','A relative clause is used to provide additional information about a noun. The sentence ''The book, which the author wrote, is on the bestseller list'' uses ''which'' correctly to introduce the relative clause.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Identify the sentence that is an example of a complex sentence','I went to the store, and I bought some milk','When I arrived, I saw my friend','I went to the store because I needed milk','The dog runs quickly across the field','B','A complex sentence contains an independent clause and a dependent clause. The sentence ''When I arrived, I saw my friend'' contains an independent clause (''I saw my friend'') and a dependent clause (''When I arrived'').','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Choose the sentence that is in the correct form of the present perfect tense','I have went to the store','I has gone to the store','I have gone to the store','I go to the store','C','The present perfect tense is formed with ''has'' or ''have'' and the past participle of the verb. The sentence ''I have gone to the store'' uses the correct form of the present perfect tense.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Which of the following sentences uses a subordinate clause correctly?','I went to the store because I need milk','I went to the store because I needed milk','I went to the store, so I bought some milk','I went to the store, although I did not need milk','B','A subordinate clause is used to show the relationship between two clauses. The sentence ''I went to the store because I needed milk'' uses the subordinate clause ''because I needed milk'' correctly to show the reason for going to the store.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Identify the sentence that is an example of a simple sentence','I went to the store, and I bought some milk','When I arrived, I saw my friend','The dog runs quickly across the field','The manager wrote the report, but the assistant edited it','C','A simple sentence contains a single independent clause. The sentence ''The dog runs quickly across the field'' contains only one independent clause.','easy',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Choose the sentence that uses the correct form of the past perfect tense','I had went to the store before it closed','I had gone to the store before it closed','I had go to the store before it closed','I had been going to the store before it closed','B','The past perfect tense is formed with ''had'' and the past participle of the verb. The sentence ''I had gone to the store before it closed'' uses the correct form of the past perfect tense.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Which of the following sentences uses a participle phrase correctly?','The dog, running quickly across the field, is very happy','The dog, runs quickly across the field, is very happy','The dog, to run quickly across the field, is very happy','The dog, running quickly, across the field is very happy','A','A participle phrase is used to provide additional information about a noun. The sentence ''The dog, running quickly across the field, is very happy'' uses the participle phrase ''running quickly across the field'' correctly to describe the dog.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Identify the sentence that is an example of a compound-complex sentence','I went to the store, and I bought some milk','When I arrived, I saw my friend, and we went to the store','The dog runs quickly across the field, but the cat is sleeping','The manager wrote the report, but the assistant edited it, and the CEO approved it','D','A compound-complex sentence contains two or more independent clauses and one or more dependent clauses. The sentence ''The manager wrote the report, but the assistant edited it, and the CEO approved it'' contains two independent clauses (''The manager wrote the report'' and ''the CEO approved it'') and a dependent clause (''but the assistant edited it'').','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Choose the sentence that uses the correct form of the future perfect tense','I will have went to the store by tomorrow','I will have gone to the store by tomorrow','I will go to the store by tomorrow','I will be going to the store by tomorrow','B','The future perfect tense is formed with ''will have'' and the past participle of the verb. The sentence ''I will have gone to the store by tomorrow'' uses the correct form of the future perfect tense.','hard',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Which of the following sentences uses a gerund phrase correctly?','I love reading books, and writing stories','I love to read books, and to write stories','I love reading books, to write stories','I love read books, and write stories','A','A gerund phrase is used to provide additional information about a noun. The sentence ''I love reading books, and writing stories'' uses the gerund phrases ''reading books'' and ''writing stories'' correctly to describe the activities.','medium',true,false,NOW()),
('unilag','Use of English','Sentence Construction',NULL,'Identify the sentence that is an example of a sentence with a dangling modifier','Having studied all night, the exam was easy','After studying all night, the exam was easy','The exam was easy, having studied all night','The exam was easy because I studied all night','A','A dangling modifier is a word or phrase that modifies the wrong noun. The sentence ''Having studied all night, the exam was easy'' has a dangling modifier because ''having studied all night'' modifies ''the exam'', not the person taking the exam.','hard',true,false,NOW())
